<br>
For some reason the child was not sacrificed. A question the child never asked, nor, did she care for an answer. The life of a solitary child in The Spires of Innoruuk was not an easy one. “Punishment” was often doled out for no apprehend reason. Many of the scars from those early years she still carries to this day, both physical and emotional. The punishment from the Priest is what she holds with her most to this day, though the Priestess’ of Innoruuk were far more creative with it. <br>
<br>
She was not given a name she was simply known as child. The teachings of Innoruuk were infused in her from the moment she learned to talk. She manifested the power to call upon Innoruuk just prior to her tenth year in the Spires. Most did not show this ability until they were adults and ready to begin their training in the forest surrounding Neriak. She first manifested the ability to heal after one of her punishments. Healing her wounds. The Priestess that administered the beating saw this and promptly beat her near to death. She let the &quot;child” know, in no uncertain terms if she ever erased a lesson again she would no longer breathe. <br>
<br>
After she recovered she was often put to work healing the minor wounds of the young warriors and wizards learning their trade in the Nektulos forest. When she wasn’t healing she was either keeping the chapel clean or immersed in Innoruuk’s scriptures. Her few moments of happiness were those times she read of Innoruuk and his Dark Saints. She often envisioned herself setting the fabled tree city of Kelethin ablaze and leading the charge on the soot covered city of Felwithe. Something, later in life she threatened the Woodefl Cabri with. All he had asked was that she waited for him to acquire a bow before she did it. The weakness of the lightdwellers has never ceased to amaze her. <br>
<br>
She was finally given a name about five years after most Tier’dal were released in to the Nektulos to seek their fortune. She was given the name Yathrin, which in an ancient form of Tier’dal, only used by the clergy, simply meant Priestess. Shortly after her eleventh season she was recruited into the Obsidian Blade and has served faithfully ever since. Many of the Blades owed their lives to her timely healing. Upon her second naming day she was given the name D’Plith, which simply means, of hate. <br>
